solutions.content:
The idea is to use binary search on the answer.
We are searching for the least x, such that there are at least k products less than or equal to x.

For each element in the array *a[n]* we perform a special binary search on the array *b[m]*, hence a total running time of *O(n.log(m).log(Range))*.
Since the order of *a* and *b* is irrelevant, this bound can further be improved to *O(min(n,m).log(max(n,m)).log(Range))*.

*How exactly do we perform the search?*

Let *the upper-bound of y* be the number of elements in *b* that are less than or equal to y.

Let x≥0. Let w>0 be an element of *a* and we want to know how many products of w with an element of *b* are less than or equal to x.
The numbers of these products is exactly *the upper-bound of (x div w)*, for instance:

x=31, w=10, b=[-5, -4, -3, -3, -2, -1, 2, 3, 3, 4, 6, 12, 13].
The number of products, less than or equal to 31 is 9.
This corresponds to the range [-5, -4, -3, -3, -2, -1, 2, 3, 3], which directly corresponds to *the upper-bound of 3*.

In case w<0 we are interested in *m - the upper-bound of (x div w)-1*.
For instance x=31, w=-10 in the above example.
The valid range of products is [-3, -3, -2, -1, 2, 3, 3, 4, 6, 12, 13].
The number of elemets here is exactly *m - the upper-bound of -4*, since the later corresponds to the remaining range [-5, -4].

In case x<0, we have some special cases, depending on whether w divides x or not.

For w>0 and w divides x we are again searching for *the upper-bound of (x div w)*.
For instance x=-30, w=10 in the above example.
The valid range is [-5, -4, -3, -3], which corresponds to the products [-50, -40, -30, -30], all less than or equal to -30.

However if w does not divide x we are searching for *the upper-bound of (x div w)-1*.
For instance x=-31, w=10. 
The valid range is now [-5, -4], which corresponds to the producuts [-50, -40].
Note that -3 is no longer in the valid range, since -30 > -31.

For w<0 and w divides x we are again searching for *m - the upper-bound of (x div w)-1*.
For instance x=-30, w=-10. 
The valid range is now [3, 3, 4, 6, 12, 13], which corresponds to the products [-30, -30, -40, -60, -120, -130], all less than or equal to -30.

However if w does not divide x we are searching for *m - the upper-bound of (x div w)*.
For instance x=-31, w=-10.
The valid range is now [4, 6, 12, 13], which corresponds to the products [-40, -60, -120, -130].
Note that 3 is now longer in the valid range, since -30 > -31.

The last remaining case is w=0, which is trivial, since all resulting products are equal to 0.
In case x≥0, we have m products less than or equal to x and in case x<0 we have no such products.

The following C solution is a straight-forward illustration of the above idea.
```
int ub(int* a, int l, int r, long long x){
    int m;
    while (l <= r){
        m = (l+r)/2;
        if (a[m] <= x) l = m+1;
        else r = m-1;
    }

    return l;
}

long long kthSmallestProduct(int* a, int n, int* b, int m, long long k){
    long long r = (long long)(1e10), l = -r, x, c;

    int i;

    while (l <= r){
        x = (l+r)/2;

        c = 0;
        for (i = 0; i < n; i++){
            if (a[i] > 0) c += ub(b, 0, m-1, x/a[i] - (x<0 && x%a[i]));
            else if (a[i] < 0) c += m - ub(b, 0, m-1, x/a[i] - !(x<0 && x%a[i]));
            else if (x >= 0) c += m;

            if (c > k-1) break;
        }

        if (c <= k-1) l = x+1;
        else r = x-1;
    }

    return l;
}
```

