This question involved using binary search on Ans-

**key idea** - we keep find out the **number of product≤ our mid value** and comparing it with our k
we keep shortening our upper bound when we have found our ans.

challenges faced-

1. **effectively calculating the number of products of array in O(N) time**
for this we maintained a 2-pointer approach , since the array was sorted , we kept our **j pointer** to **last value of second array** and **i pointer** on **first value of second array** , if that value gave the answer less  than our num, all the values before that would give the same ans, so we update the cnt as j+1 and move i pointer ahead. Once j value reaches 0, increasing i pointer would not mean much and thus we exit out the loop.

2.**handling negative numbers**

our negative number would disturb the above approach and hence we have to handle them separately.

We first check **whether k lies in the negative side and positive side**, and according to that we proceed.

eg: if k lies in negative than we need only negative numbers to check and we multiply neg1 * pos2 and neg2 * pos1;

also **value of k decide which array we have to reverse**

→if k is in negative side to effectively get negative products count we would have to r**everse positive numbers** so as to fit our above logic

eg: arr1 = [-2,-1], arr2 = [3,4]

-2 * 4 = -8  < -7 but -2 * 3 =-6 > -7

→by same logic when k is in positive side **we reverse negative numbers** to fit our logic

I have taken low and high as most minimum and maximum values but you can take them as min and max value of products array
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long getnum(vector<int>& arr1,vector<int>& arr2,vector<int>& arr3,vector<int>& arr4,long long num){
        int i = 0;
        int j = arr2.size()-1;
        long long  cnt = 0;
        while(i<arr1.size() and j>=0 and arr2.size()>0){
            if(1l*arr1[i]*arr2[j]<=num){
                i++;
                cnt+=(j+1);
            }
            else j--;
        }
        i=0;j=arr4.size()-1;
        while(i<arr3.size() and j>=0 and arr4.size()>0){
            if(1l*arr3[i]*arr4[j]<=num){
                i++;
                cnt+=(j+1);
            }
            else j--;
        }

        return cnt;
    }

    long long kthSmallestProduct(vector<int>& nums1, vector<int>& nums2, long long k) {

        vector<int> pos1;
        vector<int> neg1;
        vector<int> pos2;
        vector<int> neg2;
        for(auto x:nums1){
            if(x<0){
                neg1.push_back(x);
            }
            else{
                pos1.push_back(x);
            }
        }
        for(auto x:nums2){
            if(x<0){
                neg2.push_back(x);
            }
            else{
                pos2.push_back(x);
            }
        }
        long long nofneg  = neg1.size() * pos2.size()  + neg2.size()*pos1.size();
        bool iskneg = k>nofneg?false:true;
        k = !iskneg?k-nofneg:k;
        if(!iskneg){
            reverse(neg1.begin(),neg1.end());
            reverse(neg2.begin(),neg2.end());
        }else{
            reverse(pos1.begin(),pos1.end());
            reverse(pos2.begin(),pos2.end());
        }
        long long low = -1e10,high = 1e10;
        while(low<high){
            long long mid = (long long)(low + (high-low)/2); 
            if(getnum(pos1,iskneg?neg2:pos2,neg1,iskneg?pos2:neg2,mid)>=k){
                high = mid;
            }else{
                low = mid+1;
            }

        }
        return high;
    }
};
```

